	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I am not sure why all the people are complaining about this. <BR>
<BR>
I know all about the hassles of farming. You think getting bone chips and wolf pelts can be a hassle? Try being a rogue and acquiring all the different poison making ingredients. I've spent countless hours with my rogue friend farming. The loot code isn't saying stop that, and hopefully if Verant is thinking ahead they will not have components for stuff needed in those zones (doubtfully, but hopefully). <BR>
<BR>
The loot code is saying this - there are going to be items that high level characters won't be able to grab. These are items that high level characters probably won't want to use anyway and would only sell if they had it. Like how many characters go to Dragnor's Cauldron and say, &quot;Yes! Finally! A ruined totem staff!&quot; No, it doesn't happen. Verant is just placing things like the staff in the places it belongs. With the low level characters.<BR>
<BR>
To the person who says they can't understand why Verant is even paying attention to the low level characters because the high level characters are the ones who played the longest, that's not necessarily true. I know many people and I am one of those people who've played this game for a very long time - over a year now - and still don't have an uber character. Why? Because I like making characters. I like trying out the classes, and the races, and switching around like mad. If you read Brad's entire post on the boards he addresses just that. He says he's sorry if you people feel that this ruins the game for you, but there are many more people out there who like switching around.<BR>
<BR>
I do like the idea of equipment taking a certain skill level to use. That would stop twinking in its tracks. But, I don't think we're going to see that anytime soon on EQ.<BR>
<BR>
Fayja Quartarine<BR>
21st level druid <BR>
(with a bard, cleric, mage, and rogue all behind)
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
